title: For Sale/Trade:  ***SUPER RARE***  ASIER GUYOT RUE DE LYON 48 PINFIRE REVOLVER WITH FOLDING TRIGGER
postcontent:
Vet - Bring Back.   This was brought back during WW2 by my grandfather.  It was made by GUYOT in Paris France.  

(MARKINGS) Very hard to read, but:

•"ASIER" and then the rest is illegible (left side of barrel)
•"GUYOT RUE DE LYON 48 PARIS" (bottom pistol grip)
•"GUYOT PARIS" but if you look inside that mark you also see what looks like additional lettering, looks like a "P" inside the U of GUYOT and a "R" in the space between the U & Y (top of barrel)

From what research I've done GUYOT was a collective of highly skilled craftsmen who did extremely high end and ornate pieces (rifles, shotguns, and pistols) for the nobility of the time.  Often these pieces were 1 of 1's.  

This piece has superior scroll work on every part of the metal from top to bottom, front to back, side to side.  It is very rare to find any piece with this much scroll work.  It was recommended that this piece be professionally cleaned as it would definitely be an auction piece.

title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W Bodyguard .380 two-tone, stainless, stippled
postcontent:
I have a Smith and Wesson Bodyguard .380
It has been polished for that custom two tone look.  Slide is stainless steel. 
The grip is fully stippled to give it a real aggressive grip making it easier to hold on to. It  noticeably improved my accuracy. 

This gun is a true double action which makes it much better (in my opinion) for  ankle carry.  It has a long trigger pull like most pocket .380s but because it's a true double action if there is a misfire you can keep pulling the trigger on the same round until it goes off. I've never had it misfire but in an emergency situation you don't want to have to rack the slide to reset the firing pin before shooting again.  

I owned the Ruger LCP and I hated it. I love this gun and would trust my life with it over an lcp any day.  The biggest differences is the trigger pull, the double action,  slide lock, and safety. All these things make it a better gun.  

This gun has been my daily carry but has only seen a couple hundred rounds. And I clean it regularly. It shoots flawlessly and the laser functions well. 

Comes with two magazines. One has an extended tail piece so you can get all three figures on it.   Ankle holster  included. 

Also has a clip installed making it very easy to clip it on anything. I've even carried it in a pair of gym shorts.

title: For Sale:  Discontinued .44 Magnum Marlin 1894C
postcontent:
I bought this handsome monster in 1991 but it sat forlorn in various closets till the week before last, when I finally took it to the range to finally fire it. A mere twenty (20) rounds suggests this .44 magnum is just too much gun for me: there isn't much recoil but the very loud BOOM makes me flinch. And my bills were more than I'd expected so...

It's in great shape, with a cross-bar safety, a blued finish, the standard walnut stock, a hammer extension I see no need to remove, and a vaunted Micro-Groove barrel. (Wikipedia says "in the mid-1990s, Marlin changed the .357 and .44 barrels from 12-groove-or-more 'Micro-Groove' rifling to 6-groove 'Ballard' style rifling.") 

The only things wrong with this gun are cosmetic: there are a couple of superficial scratches and a tiny ding or two in the wood finish, and now there are a couple ugly but not fatal scratches on the sight base from my recent first attempt to replace a broken rear sight folding leaf (see photo), which by the way has been replaced and installed. Otherwise it's a fine, barely used example of a model Marlin doesn't make anymore. If those scratches in the rear sight base matter to you feel free to buy yourself one from Midway for $12.99 +S&H; the main reason I'm selling this rifle is that I'm broke enough for such small sums to count.

Of course I'm open to partial trades and best offers, but as anybody old enough to buy a firearm knows there's a difference between "broke" and "desperate." If it was that bad I'd have taken Bud's offer last week. You know what I'm saying?
